# Model Card — OneHealth FundScore

**Scenario:** OneHealth FundScore: Grant Allocation Risk Predictor
**Authors:** Timothy Ojodare
**Date:** April 1, 2026

---

## 1. Model Details

> What model or API is being used? Who built it? What version? What type of
> model — classification, prediction, generation, optimization? When was it
> developed?

OneHealth FundScore is a multi-layer neural network designed for risk prediction and scoring (any possible output value between 0–100 scale), does not make funding decision by classifying what to, and what not to fund. It functions as a composite risk index generator that produces a country-level One Health risk score by integrating epidemiological, veterinary, environmental, and institutional data streams of applicants. The model was developed by OneHealth Fundscore for use by an international funding agency in its annual $120 million grant allocation cycle.

The system is designed to ingest structured country application data that include epidemiological data (disease burden, outbreak history, surveillance capacity), veterinary and livestock data (zoonotic disease prevalence, antimicrobial resistance patterns), environmental indicators (deforestation rates, biodiversity loss indices, water and sanitation coverage), and institutional capacity metrics (health workforce density, laboratory capacity, IHR core capacity scores), and the system processes these input data alongside external datasets from the WHO Global Health Observatory, OIE/WOAH disease notification systems, World Bank development indicators, and the INFORM Risk Index. Outputs include the cummulative risk score and a domain-level breakdown (highlighting the one that contributes the most to the cummulative score) across four risk pillars: zoonotic spillover risk, antimicrobial resistance (AMR) burden, environmental degradation, and institutional fragility.

The model version, training framework (which includes the data and how it was collected, and at what time period), and architecture depth (number of layers, review triggers and retraining details) are not disclosed. This is a transparency gap that itself warrants documentation, for a system influencing $120 million in annual funding, the opacity of these information is a significant as it directly weighs heavily on the quality of funding decisons.

